❯ What is the mode for torch.compile in vLLM V1? How does it different from SGLang?                                                                                             

● Searched for 17 patterns, read 5 files (ctrl+o to expand)

● Now I have everything I need.

  ---
  torch.compile: vLLM V1 vs SGLang

  ---
  vLLM V1

  Default: ON — via optimization_level=O2 (default), which sets mode=VLLM_COMPILE (mode 3).

  # config/vllm.py:817-819
  if self.compilation_config.mode is None:
      if self.optimization_level > OptimizationLevel.O0:
          self.compilation_config.mode = CompilationMode.VLLM_COMPILE  # mode=3

  vLLM has 4 compilation modes:

  ┌──────┬─────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ Mode │        Name         │                 Description                 │
  ├──────┼─────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ 0    │ NONE                │ Pure eager, no compilation                  │
  ├──────┼─────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ 1    │ STOCK_TORCH_COMPILE │ Standard torch.compile, whole graph         │
  ├──────┼─────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ 2    │ DYNAMO_TRACE_ONCE   │ Single Dynamo trace, no recompile           │
  ├──────┼─────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ 3    │ VLLM_COMPILE        │ Default — custom piecewise Inductor backend │
  └──────┴─────────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Mode 3 (VLLM_COMPILE) is architecturally unique:

  Full model graph
          │
          ▼ Dynamo traces
   FX Graph (full)
          │
          ▼ split at "splitting_ops" (attention ops)
   [subgraph_0] → [attention] → [subgraph_1] → [attention] → [subgraph_2]
     compiled           not          compiled         not          compiled
     by Inductor      compiled      by Inductor     compiled     by Inductor
          │
          ▼ Custom passes applied BEFORE Inductor codegen:
     - fuse_norm_quant  (RMSNorm + FP8 quant)
     - fuse_act_quant   (SiLU×Mul + FP8 quant)
     - fuse_allreduce_rms (allreduce + RMSNorm, Hopper/Blackwell only)
     - eliminate_noops
     - combo_kernels    (horizontal fusion, e.g. QK-norm + rope)

  Inductor configuration for single-size batches:
  # compiler_interface.py:679-682
  config["max_autotune"] = envs.VLLM_ENABLE_INDUCTOR_MAX_AUTOTUNE  # True by default
  config["coordinate_descent_tuning"] = ...  # True by default

  CUDAGraph mode (default FULL_AND_PIECEWISE):
  - Decode batches → FULL CUDAGraph (whole step captured)
  - Prefill/mixed batches → PIECEWISE CUDAGraph (only non-attention subgraphs captured)

  Dynamic shapes: DynamicShapesType.BACKED by default — Dynamo traces once, drops shape guards, compiled graph runs for any size.

  ---
  SGLang

  Default: OFF — enable_torch_compile=False in ServerArgs.

  When enabled (--enable-torch-compile):

  # cuda_graph_runner.py:134-140
  yield torch.compile(
      torch.no_grad()(model.forward),
      mode=os.environ.get("SGLANG_TORCH_COMPILE_MODE", "max-autotune-no-cudagraphs"),
      dynamic=False,
  )

  Single mode: max-autotune-no-cudagraphs (standard PyTorch mode, no custom backend).

  # cuda_graph_runner.py:149-162 — set_torch_compile_config()
  torch._inductor.config.coordinate_descent_tuning = True
  torch._inductor.config.triton.unique_kernel_names = True
  torch._inductor.config.fx_graph_cache = True
  torch._dynamo.config.cache_size_limit = 1024

  Only applies to batch sizes ≤ torch_compile_max_bs (default 32):
  compile_bs = [1, 2, 4, ..., 32]   # compiled
  capture_bs = [1, 2, 4, ..., 160]  # cuda-graph captured (all sizes)
  Sizes above 32 run without torch.compile even when enabled.

  ---
  Side-by-Side Comparison

  ┌────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │     Dimension      │                      vLLM V1                      │                                            SGLang                                             │
  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Default state      │ ON (at O2)                                        │ OFF (opt-in)                                                                                  │
  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Compilation mode   │ VLLM_COMPILE (custom piecewise Inductor)          │ max-autotune-no-cudagraphs (stock PyTorch)                                                    │
  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Graph scope        │ Piecewise — splits at attention, compiles         │ Whole model forward (single graph)                                                            │
  │                    │ surrounding subgraphs                             │                                                                                               │
  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Attention handling │ Excluded from compiled subgraph (splitting_ops)   │ Included in compiled graph                                                                    │
  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Custom IR passes   │ Yes — norm fusion, quant fusion, allreduce        │ No — relies on Inductor's built-in passes only                                                │
  │                    │ fusion, etc.                                      │                                                                                               │
  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ max_autotune       │ Yes, for single-size shapes                       │ Yes, always (max-autotune-...)                                                                │
  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ dynamic            │ Not set (backed dynamic shapes)                   │ dynamic=False (fully static)                                                                  │
  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ CUDAGraph          │ Orthogonal — FULL+PIECEWISE cudagraphs on top of  │ Separate — -no-cudagraphs explicitly disables torch.compile's internal CUDA graph; SGLang     │
  │ relationship       │ compiled subgraphs                                │ manages graphs via its own CudaGraphRunner                                                    │
  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Batch size         │ All captured cudagraph sizes                      │ Only ≤ torch_compile_max_bs (default 32)                                                      │
  │ coverage           │                                                   │                                                                                               │
  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Backend            │ Custom VllmInductorBackend                        │ Stock inductor                                                                                │
  └────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Key Architectural Difference

  The fundamental split is who manages CUDA graphs:

  - vLLM: torch.compile (VLLM_COMPILE) and CUDA graph capture are co-designed — piecewise compilation produces subgraphs that are precisely what gets captured in CUDA graphs.
  They work together.
  - SGLang: torch.compile and CUDA graphs are independent layers — SGLang's CudaGraphRunner captures the CUDA graph at the Python level, and optionally torch.compile (with
  -no-cudagraphs) optimizes the Triton kernels inside that graph without interfering with the outer capture. The -no-cudagraphs suffix is explicitly to prevent torch.compile
  from trying to manage CUDA graphs internally while SGLang does so externally, which would conflict.

❯ Compare vLLM and SGLang in a way they transmit the data. Does vLLM has more efficiency since it uses a dedicated cuda stream and reusing cpu buffer other than tolist?        

● This is a great question. The answer is no — vLLM's better transfer mechanism is outweighed by SGLang's much smaller transfer volume. Let me break it down precisely.

  ---
  The Two Dimensions of Transfer Efficiency

  1. Transfer Mechanism — how data moves (vLLM's strength)
  2. Transfer Volume — how much data moves (SGLang's strength)

  ---
  CPU → GPU: Mechanism vs Volume

  vLLM's mechanism advantages:

  - Pre-allocated pinned CPU buffers reused every step — no malloc/free, DMA engine can read directly without staging
  - non_blocking=True with prepare_inputs_event — CPU continues scheduling while DMA runs
  - Zero Python allocation overhead

  SGLang's mechanism disadvantages:

  - Creates new CPU tensors every step: torch.tensor(python_list, dtype=...).to(device, non_blocking=True)
  - Incurs Python list → tensor allocation cost each step
  - Still non_blocking=True, so DMA is async, but with fresh allocations

  But look at the volumes:

  ┌──────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────┐
  │              │            vLLM Decode             │      SGLang Decode      │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
  │ input_ids    │ [2048] int32 = 8 KB (CPU→GPU)      │ 0 B (GPU tensor reused) │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
  │ block table  │ [2048, 256] int32 = 2 MB (CPU→GPU) │ 0 B (GPU-resident)      │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
  │ slot_mapping │ [2048] int64 = 16 KB (CPU→GPU)     │ 0 B (Triton kernel)     │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
  │ seq_lens     │ [2048] int32 = 8 KB (CPU→GPU)      │ 8 KB (CPU→GPU)          │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
  │ Total        │ ~2.1 MB                            │ ~8 KB                   │
  └──────────────┴────────────────────────────────────┴─────────────────────────┘

  On PCIe 4.0 x16 (~25 GB/s practical):
  - vLLM block table DMA alone: 2 MB ÷ 25 GB/s ≈ 80 μs
  - SGLang total: 8 KB ÷ 25 GB/s ≈ 0.3 μs

  vLLM's pinned memory and async streams can at best optimize the transfer time of those 2 MB, not eliminate it. The prepare_inputs_event mechanism means the CPU doesn't block
  — but the DMA engine still spends ~80 μs every decode step moving the block table. No amount of stream optimization can make 2 MB faster than 8 KB.

  ---
  GPU → CPU: vLLM Has a Real Advantage Here

  vLLM (async mode):

  GPU forward pass (stream 0)
         │
         ├──► async_output_copy_stream.wait_stream(stream 0)
         │         sampled_tokens.to("cpu", non_blocking=True)  ← runs in background
         │
         └──► CPU: schedule next batch immediately
                   (tolist() consumed later, already done)

  SGLang:

  GPU forward pass
         │
         └──► next_token_ids.tolist()   ← BLOCKING SYNC
                    │
                    └──► CPU: schedule next batch

  .tolist() forces a full CPU-GPU synchronization — the CPU stalls waiting for:
  1. GPU to finish the forward pass
  2. Data to be copied to CPU
  3. Converted to Python list

  vLLM's async stream genuinely overlaps this copy with the next step's CPU scheduling work. This is vLLM's real, meaningful advantage — it hides the GPU→CPU latency inside the
   CPU scheduling time.

  However, both sides transfer tiny output tensors (~8-16 KB), so the absolute time saved is small (< 1 μs DMA + sync overhead).

  ---
  Net Verdict

  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────┬────────────────┬────────────────────────┬───────────────┐
  │                Dimension                 │      vLLM      │         SGLang         │    Winner     │
  ├──────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────────────┼───────────────┤
  │ CPU→GPU mechanism (pinned, async, reuse) │ ✅ Better      │ ❌ New alloc each step │ vLLM          │
  ├──────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────────────┼───────────────┤
  │ CPU→GPU volume (decode)                  │ ❌ 2.1 MB      │ ✅ 8 KB                │ SGLang (262×) │
  ├──────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────────────┼───────────────┤
  │ GPU→CPU mechanism (async stream)         │ ✅ Truly async │ ❌ Blocking .tolist()  │ vLLM          │
  ├──────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────────────┼───────────────┤
  │ GPU→CPU volume                           │ ❌ 16 KB       │ ✅ 8 KB                │ SGLang        │
  ├──────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────────────┼───────────────┤
  │ Overall decode bandwidth                 │ ~2.1 MB/step   │ ~8 KB/step             │ SGLang        │
  └──────────────────────────────────────────┴────────────────┴────────────────────────┴───────────────┘

  SGLang wins overall, because the volume difference (262×) completely dominates the mechanism difference (~10–20% improvement from pinned/async). vLLM's streaming
  optimizations are micro-optimizations applied to a macro problem (large block table transfers).

  vLLM's one genuine pipelining advantage is the async GPU→CPU output copy — it hides GPU→CPU latency inside CPU scheduling. SGLang's .tolist() stalls the pipeline every step.
  But since both transfer only ~8-16 KB of output, the absolute latency difference is negligible (< 1 μs).

  The root cause of vLLM's bandwidth problem is architectural: copying the entire block table every step regardless of what changed. SGLang avoids this entirely by making the
  KV cache index (req_to_token) a GPU-resident structure and using Triton kernels to build attention metadata directly on the GPU.


  ---
  SGLang CPU ↔ GPU Data Transfer Analysis

  Setup & Assumptions

  ┌────────────────────────┬──────────────────┐
  │       Parameter        │      Value       │
  ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────┤
  │ max-running-requests   │ 2,048            │
  ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────┤
  │ max-prefill-tokens     │ 8,192            │
  ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────┤
  │ input_len / output_len │ 128 / 128 tokens │
  ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────┤
  │ num-prompts            │ 5,000            │
  └────────────────────────┴──────────────────┘

  Batch sizing:
  - Prefill: min(8192/128, 2048) = 64 reqs/batch, 8,192 tokens
  - Decode (peak): 2,048 reqs, 2,048 tokens (1 token/req)

  All transfers use .to(device, non_blocking=True). There are no pre-allocated pinned CPU buffers like vLLM — tensors are freshly created on CPU and transferred each step.

  ---
  1. CPU → GPU

  1-1. Prefill (64 reqs, 8,192 tokens)

  Source: schedule_batch.py::prepare_for_extend() + forward_batch_info.py::init_new()

  ┌──────────────────────┬─────────┬───────┬────────┐
  │        Tensor        │  Shape  │ dtype │  Size  │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼────────┤
  │ input_ids            │ [8,192] │ int64 │ 64 KB  │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼────────┤
  │ req_pool_indices     │ [64]    │ int64 │ 512 B  │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼────────┤
  │ seq_lens             │ [64]    │ int64 │ 512 B  │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼────────┤
  │ orig_seq_lens        │ [64]    │ int32 │ 256 B  │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼────────┤
  │ prefix_lens          │ [64]    │ int64 │ 512 B  │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼────────┤
  │ extend_seq_lens      │ [64]    │ int32 │ 256 B  │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼────────┤
  │ extend_prefix_lens   │ [64]    │ int32 │ 256 B  │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼────────┤
  │ num_token_non_padded │ scalar  │ int32 │ 4 B    │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼────────┤
  │ Total                │         │       │ ~66 KB │
  └──────────────────────┴─────────┴───────┴────────┘

  - out_cache_loc (KV slot indices): already a GPU tensor — returned directly from token_to_kv_pool_allocator.alloc() which operates on GPU-resident free lists.
  - positions: computed on GPU via compute_position() using the already-transferred extend_seq_lens and extend_prefix_lens.
  - kv_indptr / kv_indices / kv_last_page_len: built on GPU by the Triton kernel create_flashinfer_kv_indices_triton() from the GPU-resident req_to_token pool.

  1-2. Decode (2,048 reqs, 2,048 tokens)

  Source: schedule_batch.py::prepare_for_decode()

  ┌──────────────────────────┬─────────┬───────┬───────┐
  │          Tensor          │  Shape  │ dtype │ Size  │
  ├──────────────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼───────┤
  │ seq_lens (for kv_indptr) │ [2,048] │ int32 │ 8 KB  │
  ├──────────────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼───────┤
  │ Total                    │         │       │ ~8 KB │
  └──────────────────────────┴─────────┴───────┴───────┘

  This 8 KB comes from seq_lens_cpu (Python list) → paged_kernel_lens GPU tensor (torch.tensor(seq_lens_cpu, dtype=torch.int32, device="cuda")) inside init_flashinfer_args(),
  used to compute kv_indptr via torch.cumsum().

  Everything else is zero-copy:
  - input_ids = batch.output_ids — the GPU tensor from the previous step's sampler output assigned directly (batch.output_ids = next_token_ids at scheduler.py:1838) — no CPU
  roundtrip.
  - seq_lens — incremented in-place on GPU: self.seq_lens.add_(1).
  - out_cache_loc — allocated directly as GPU tensor via alloc_token_slots().
  - positions — computed on GPU from seq_lens.
  - kv_indptr / kv_indices — updated by Triton kernel from GPU-resident req_to_token pool ([2048, max_context_len] int32).
  - CUDA graph copies (input_ids, seq_lens, out_cache_loc, positions, req_pool_indices) are all GPU→GPU scatter into the static graph buffers.

  ---
  2. GPU → CPU

  2-1. Prefill Output

  ┌────────────────┬───────┬───────────────────┬───────┐
  │     Tensor     │ Shape │       dtype       │ Size  │
  ├────────────────┼───────┼───────────────────┼───────┤
  │ next_token_ids │ [64]  │ int32 → list[int] │ 256 B │
  └────────────────┴───────┴───────────────────┴───────┘

  Via .tolist() at scheduler_output_processor_mixin.py:59.

  2-2. Decode Output

  ┌────────────────┬─────────┬───────────────────┬──────┐
  │     Tensor     │  Shape  │       dtype       │ Size │
  ├────────────────┼─────────┼───────────────────┼──────┤
  │ next_token_ids │ [2,048] │ int32 → list[int] │ 8 KB │
  └────────────────┴─────────┴───────────────────┴──────┘

  Via .tolist() at scheduler_output_processor_mixin.py:216.

  ---
  Architectural Contrast: SGLang vs vLLM

  ┌────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │                │           vLLM Decode (per step)            │               SGLang Decode (per step)               │
  ├────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ block table    │ [2048, 256] int32 = 2 MB (explicit CPU→GPU) │ 0 B — req_to_token is GPU-resident, updated in-place │
  ├────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ input_ids      │ [2048] int32 = 8 KB (explicit CPU→GPU)      │ 0 B — GPU tensor reused directly                     │
  ├────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ seq_lens       │ [2048] int32 = 8 KB (explicit CPU→GPU)      │ 8 KB (for kv_indptr computation only)                │
  ├────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ slot_mapping   │ [2048] int64 = 16 KB (explicit CPU→GPU)     │ 0 B — Triton kernel computes kv_indices on GPU       │
  ├────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ sampled tokens │ [2048,1] int64 = 16 KB                      │ [2048] int32 = 8 KB                                  │
  ├────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Total CPU→GPU  │ ~2.1 MB                                     │ ~8 KB                                                │
  ├────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Total GPU→CPU  │ ~16 KB                                      │ ~8 KB                                                │
  └────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  The 262× difference in CPU→GPU bandwidth comes from two key SGLang design decisions:
  1. GPU-resident req_to_token pool ([max_running_requests, max_context_len] int32, updated via GPU scatter ops) — eliminates the block table transfer entirely.
  2. GPU tensor reuse for input_ids — sampler output (batch.output_ids) is assigned directly as the next step's input_ids without ever leaving the GPU.

  ---
  vLLM CPU ↔ GPU Data Transfer Analysis

  Setup & Assumptions

  ┌─────────────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────┐
  │              Parameter              │        Value        │
  ├─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┤
  │ max_num_seqs (= max_num_reqs)       │ 2,048               │
  ├─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┤
  │ max_num_batched_tokens              │ 8,192               │
  ├─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┤
  │ input_len / output_len              │ 128 / 128 tokens    │
  ├─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┤
  │ num_prompts                         │ 5,000               │
  ├─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┤
  │ block_size (default FlashAttention) │ 16 tokens           │
  ├─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┤
  │ max_model_len (e.g., LLaMA-2)       │ 4,096 tokens        │
  ├─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┤
  │ max_num_blocks_per_req              │ ceil(4096/16) = 256 │
  └─────────────────────────────────────┴─────────────────────┘

  Batch sizing:
  - Prefill: min(8192/128, 2048) = 64 reqs/batch, 8,192 tokens total
  - Decode (peak): 2,048 reqs/batch (1 token/req), 2,048 tokens total

  All transfers use CpuGpuBuffer.copy_to_gpu() → gpu[:n].copy_(cpu[:n], non_blocking=True).

  ---
  1. CPU → GPU

  1-1. Prefill (64 reqs, 8,192 tokens per batch)

  ┌──────────────────────┬───────────┬───────┬─────────┐
  │        Tensor        │   Shape   │ dtype │  Size   │
  ├──────────────────────┼───────────┼───────┼─────────┤
  │ input_ids            │ [8,192]   │ int32 │ 32 KB   │
  ├──────────────────────┼───────────┼───────┼─────────┤
  │ positions            │ [8,192]   │ int64 │ 64 KB   │
  ├──────────────────────┼───────────┼───────┼─────────┤
  │ query_start_loc      │ [65]      │ int32 │ 260 B   │
  ├──────────────────────┼───────────┼───────┼─────────┤
  │ seq_lens             │ [64]      │ int32 │ 256 B   │
  ├──────────────────────┼───────────┼───────┼─────────┤
  │ discard_request_mask │ [64]      │ bool  │ 64 B    │
  ├──────────────────────┼───────────┼───────┼─────────┤
  │ block_table ★        │ [64, 256] │ int32 │ 64 KB   │
  ├──────────────────────┼───────────┼───────┼─────────┤
  │ slot_mapping         │ [8,192]   │ int64 │ 64 KB   │
  ├──────────────────────┼───────────┼───────┼─────────┤
  │ Total                │           │       │ ~224 KB │
  └──────────────────────┴───────────┴───────┴─────────┘

  ★ block_table copies all 256 columns per row (commit_block_table(num_reqs) → full row copy), even though only 8 blocks/req are populated at prefill time (ceil(128/16)=8). 248
   columns are wasted bandwidth.

  1-2. Decode (2,048 reqs, 2,048 tokens per batch — peak)

  ┌──────────────────────┬──────────────┬───────┬─────────────────┐
  │        Tensor        │    Shape     │ dtype │      Size       │
  ├──────────────────────┼──────────────┼───────┼─────────────────┤
  │ input_ids            │ [2,048]      │ int32 │ 8 KB            │
  ├──────────────────────┼──────────────┼───────┼─────────────────┤
  │ positions            │ [2,048]      │ int64 │ 16 KB           │
  ├──────────────────────┼──────────────┼───────┼─────────────────┤
  │ query_start_loc      │ [2,049]      │ int32 │ 8 KB            │
  ├──────────────────────┼──────────────┼───────┼─────────────────┤
  │ seq_lens             │ [2,048]      │ int32 │ 8 KB            │
  ├──────────────────────┼──────────────┼───────┼─────────────────┤
  │ discard_request_mask │ [2,048]      │ bool  │ 2 KB            │
  ├──────────────────────┼──────────────┼───────┼─────────────────┤
  │ block_table ★★       │ [2,048, 256] │ int32 │ 2,048 KB (2 MB) │
  ├──────────────────────┼──────────────┼───────┼─────────────────┤
  │ slot_mapping         │ [2,048]      │ int64 │ 16 KB           │
  ├──────────────────────┼──────────────┼───────┼─────────────────┤
  │ Total                │              │       │ ~2.1 MB         │
  └──────────────────────┴──────────────┴───────┴─────────────────┘

  ★★ block_table dominates completely. At decode step 128 (end of generation), each request uses only ceil(256/16)=16 blocks, yet all 256 columns are transferred. That's 93.75%
   wasted bandwidth in the block table alone.

  ---
  2. GPU → CPU

  Mechanism: GPU sampler writes token IDs → pinned CPU buffer via .copy_(non_blocking=True) + CUDA event sync → .tolist().

  2-1. Prefill Output

  ┌───────────────────┬─────────┬───────┬───────┐
  │      Tensor       │  Shape  │ dtype │ Size  │
  ├───────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼───────┤
  │ sampled_token_ids │ [64, 1] │ int64 │ 512 B │
  ├───────────────────┼─────────┼───────┼───────┤
  │ Total             │         │       │ 512 B │
  └───────────────────┴─────────┴───────┴───────┘

  Only the last token of each prefill sequence is sampled and returned. Negligible.

  2-2. Decode Output

  ┌───────────────────┬────────────┬───────┬───────┐
  │      Tensor       │   Shape    │ dtype │ Size  │
  ├───────────────────┼────────────┼───────┼───────┤
  │ sampled_token_ids │ [2,048, 1] │ int64 │ 16 KB │
  ├───────────────────┼────────────┼───────┼───────┤
  │ Total             │            │       │ 16 KB │
  └───────────────────┴────────────┴───────┴───────┘

  Each of the 2,048 active requests produces one token per decode step.

  ---
  Benchmark-Scale Totals (5,000 prompts)

  ┌─────────┬────────────────────────────────────┬───────────────────┬───────────────────┐
  │  Phase  │              Batches               │ Per-batch CPU→GPU │ Per-batch GPU→CPU │
  ├─────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────┼───────────────────┤
  │ Prefill │ ceil(5000/64) = 79                 │ ~224 KB           │ 512 B             │
  ├─────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────┼───────────────────┤
  │ Decode  │ (5000×128)/2048 ≈ 313 full batches │ ~2.1 MB           │ 16 KB             │
  └─────────┴────────────────────────────────────┴───────────────────┴───────────────────┘

  ┌───────────┬───────────────────────┬───────────────────────┬─────────────┐
  │ Direction │    Total (prefill)    │    Total (decode)     │ Grand Total │
  ├───────────┼───────────────────────┼───────────────────────┼─────────────┤
  │ CPU → GPU │ 79 × 224 KB ≈ 17.3 MB │ 313 × 2.1 MB ≈ 657 MB │ ~675 MB     │
  ├───────────┼───────────────────────┼───────────────────────┼─────────────┤
  │ GPU → CPU │ 79 × 512 B ≈ 40 KB    │ 313 × 16 KB ≈ 5 MB    │ ~5 MB       │
  └───────────┴───────────────────────┴───────────────────────┴─────────────┘

  ---
  Key Observations

  1. Block table is the dominant transfer during decode: 2 MB per step vs. ~58 KB for all other tensors combined. This scales with max_num_reqs × max_num_blocks_per_req × 4
  bytes.
  2. GPU→CPU is asymmetric and tiny: Only sampled token IDs are returned (~16 KB/step decode, negligible prefill). The model logits (GBs) are consumed entirely on-GPU by the
  sampler.
  3. Prefill is transfer-light relative to decode: ~224 KB/batch for prefill vs. ~2.1 MB/batch for decode. The block_table at prefill time is 64× smaller than at decode peak.
  4. Async mode optimization: With --enable-async-output-proc, sampled token IDs are transferred on a separate CUDA stream (output_proc_stream) via pinned memory, overlapping
  with the next forward pass.
  5. Input embeddings (if --prompt-adapter or multimodal): additional [8192, hidden_size] float16/bfloat16 tensor per prefill batch — e.g., for hidden_size=4096: 64 MB/batch —
  but absent in standard text benchmarks.

❯ What are differences between  Inductor-generated Triton kernels (autotuned) and Hand-written CUDA/Triton custom ops? Can Inductor-generated Triton kernels (autotuned) be     
less efficient?                                                                                                                                                                 
                                                                                                                                                                                
● This is a deep question. Let me look at concrete examples in the SGLang codebase first, then explain the architectural differences.                                           
                                                                      
● Searched for 3 patterns, read 2 files (ctrl+o to expand)     
                                                                                                                                                                                
● Bash(grep -rn "silu_and_mul\|rmsnorm\|fused_add_rmsnorm" /root/miniconda3/envs/sglang-vllm-latest/lib/python3.10/site-packages/sglang/srt/layers/layernorm.py | head…)
  ⎿  47:        from flashinfer.norm import fused_add_rmsnorm                                                                                                                   
     49:        from sgl_kernel import fused_add_rmsnorm              
     50:    from sgl_kernel import gemma_fused_add_rmsnorm, gemma_rmsnorm, rmsnorm                                                                                              
     … +7 lines (ctrl+o to expand)                                                                                                                                              
                                                                                                                                                                                
● Now I have concrete code to illustrate this clearly.                                                                                                                          
                                                                                                                                                                      
  ---                                                                                                                                                                           
  Inductor-Generated vs Hand-Written Custom Kernels                                                                                                                             
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Concrete Example: RMSNorm with Residual                                                                                                                                       
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Hand-written (forward_cuda) — calls fused_add_rmsnorm from sgl_kernel/flashinfer:                                                                                             
  One CUDA kernel launch:                                                                                                                                                       
    READ:  x[N, H], residual[N, H], weight[H]    (2N·H + H elements)                                                                                                            
    DO:    x += residual  (fused in registers)                                                                                                                                  
           variance = mean(x²) over H                                                                                                                                           
           x = x / sqrt(variance + ε) * weight   (fused in registers)                                                                                                           
    WRITE: x[N, H], residual[N, H]               (2N·H elements)                                                                                                                
    HBM round trips: 1                                                                                                                                                          
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Native (forward_native) — standard PyTorch ops:                                                                                                                               
  x = x.to(torch.float32)           # kernel 1: type cast, write temp                                                                                                           
  x = x + residual.to(torch.float32)  # kernel 2: cast + add, write temp                                                                                                        
  residual = x.to(orig_dtype)        # kernel 3: cast, write temp                                                                                                               
  variance = (x**2).mean(-1)         # kernel 4: square + reduce, write temp                                                                                                    
  x = x * torch.rsqrt(variance+eps)  # kernel 5: div, write temp                                                                                                                
  out = (x * self.weight).to(dtype)  # kernel 6: scale + cast, write                                                                                                            
  # 6+ separate kernel launches, 6+ HBM round trips                                                                                                                             
                                                                                                                                                                                
  With Inductor (forward_native + torch.compile):                                                                                                                               
  Inductor fuses these into 1-2 Triton kernels — closing most of the gap. But the hand-written kernel still has advantages described below.                                     
                                                                                                                                                                                
  ---                                                                                                                                                                           
  Concrete Example: SiluAndMul                                                                                                                                                  
                                                                                                                                                                                
  ┌─────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────┬───────────┐
  │                             │                    Code                    │      Kernel launches       │ HBM reads │                                                         
  ├─────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────┼───────────┤                                                         
  │ forward_cuda                │ silu_and_mul(x, out) — single fused kernel │ 1                          │ x once    │                                                         
  ├─────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────┼───────────┤                                                         
  │ forward_native (no compile) │ F.silu(x[:d]) * x[d:]                      │ 3 (slice+silu, slice, mul) │ x 2-3x    │                                                         
  ├─────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────┼───────────┤                                                         
  │ forward_native + Inductor   │ fused Triton                               │ 1                          │ x once    │                                                         
  └─────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────┴───────────┘                                                         
                  
  ---
  The 5 Core Differences
                                                                                                                                                                                
  1. In-Place Memory Semantics
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Hand-written kernels often write back into the input buffer:                                                                                                                  
  // fused_add_rmsnorm — operates in-place on x and residual                                                                                                                    
  x[i] = (x[i] + residual[i]) / rms * weight[i];  // no extra allocation                                                                                                        
  residual[i] = x[i] + residual[i];               // updated in-place   
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Inductor's autograd safety model cannot generate in-place writes to inputs by default — it creates new output tensors. This adds one extra HBM write per fused op, which at   
  memory-bandwidth-bound batch sizes (decode, small bs) is a real cost.                                                                                                         
                                                                                                                                                                                
  2. Hardware-Specific Vectorization                                                                                                                                            
                  
  Hand-written kernels use architecture-specific intrinsics:                                                                                                                    
  // Custom RMSNorm: vectorized 8 elements per thread for H100
  float8 x_vec = *reinterpret_cast<float8*>(x + i);  // vectorized load                                                                                                         
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Inductor generates generic Triton that uses autotuning to find the right vectorization width. It usually gets close but may miss optimal configs for specific shapes like     
  hidden_size=4096 at bs=1.                                                                                                                                                     
                                                                                                                                                                                
  3. Algorithm vs. Kernel Optimization                                                                                                                                          
                  
  This is the most important case. Some custom kernels don't just fuse operations — they implement a fundamentally different algorithm:                                         
   
  FlashAttention custom kernel:                                                                                                                                                 
    Algorithm: Online softmax with IO-aware tiling
    - Never materializes the full [seq_len, seq_len] attention matrix
    - Reads Q/K/V in tiles, computes running max/sum                                                                                                                            
    - O(seq_len) HBM usage instead of O(seq_len²)                                                                                                                               
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Inductor's generated kernel:                                                                                                                                                  
    Algorithm: Standard attention                                                                                                                                               
    - Computes full scores = Q @ K.T              → writes [seq_len, seq_len] to HBM                                                                                            
    - Softmax(scores)                             → reads + writes [seq_len, seq_len]                                                                                           
    - output = softmax @ V                        → reads [seq_len, seq_len]                                                                                                    
    - HBM usage: O(seq_len²) — completely different complexity class                                                                                                            
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Inductor cannot invent FlashAttention. This is why SGLang's attention stays on forward_cuda regardless.                                                                       
                                                                                                                                                                                
  4. Cross-Layer Fusion                                                                                                                                                         
                  
  Hand-written kernels can encode domain knowledge across layer boundaries:                                                                                                     
  Custom: AllReduce + RMSNorm fused kernel
    - Starts norm computation while AllReduce data is arriving                                                                                                                  
    - Overlaps communication with computation                                                                                                                                   
    - 1 synchronization point                                                                                                                                                   
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Inductor: sees AllReduce as opaque, cannot fuse across it                                                                                                                     
    - AllReduce completes → barrier → RMSNorm starts                                                                                                                            
    - 2 separate phases                                                                                                                                                         
                                                                                                                                                                                
  5. Tuning Search Space                                                                                                                                                        
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Hand-written: single manually-benchmarked config                                                                                                                              
    - Engineer ran nsight, profiled at hidden_size=4096, bs=1                                                                                                                   
    - Found: block_size=128, warps=4, vectorize=8 → 95% of peak bandwidth                                                                                                       
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Inductor max-autotune: searches a predefined grid                                                                                                                             
    - block_sizes: [16, 32, 64, 128, 256]                                                                                                                                       
    - num_warps: [2, 4, 8]                                                                                                                                                      
    - num_stages: [1, 2, 3, 4]                                                                                                                                                  
    → benchmarks all combinations, picks fastest                                                                                                                                
    → may find 93% of peak, or may find 96% if hand-tuned was suboptimal                                                                                                        
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Inductor can actually beat a lazily hand-tuned kernel through autotuning, but rarely beats a carefully tuned one for the specific target shape.                               
                                                                                                                                                                                
  ---                                                                                                                                                                           
  When Inductor-Generated Kernels Are LESS Efficient
                                                    
  ┌────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │            Case            │                             Why Inductor Loses                             │                          How Much                           │     
  ├────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ FlashAttention / PagedAttn │ Algorithmic difference (tiling, online softmax)                            │ Cannot match — different complexity                         │     
  ├────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ FusedMoE (bs > 1)          │ Data-dependent routing; sparse gather/scatter not fuseable                 │ Significantly slower (that's why SGLang keeps forward_cuda) │     
  ├────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤     
  │ Memory-bound decode (bs=1) │ In-place writes; hand-tuned vectorization for exact hidden_size            │ ~5-15% slower in practice                                   │     
  ├────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤     
  │ AllReduce-fused norms      │ Cannot fuse across communication ops                                       │ Adds latency from extra sync                                │
  ├────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤     
  │ FP8 quantized matmul       │ Custom kernels exploit hardware FP8 units; Inductor may use FP16 fallbacks │ Large gap on H100                                           │
  └────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘     
                  
  When Inductor-Generated Kernels Can WIN                                                                                                                                       
                  
  ┌───────────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐                                             
  │               Case                │                                     Why Inductor Wins                                     │
  ├───────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Non-fused custom ops              │ Two separate custom kernels (e.g., norm + slice) fused into one by Inductor               │
  ├───────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Poorly tuned hand-written kernels │ Autotuning finds better block/warp config than the manual choice                          │                                             
  ├───────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤                                             
  │ Novel fusion patterns             │ Inductor spots linear + gelu + linear as fuseable; no custom kernel exists                │                                             
  ├───────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤                                             
  │ Shape-specific small ops          │ At bs=1, hidden_size operations where the search finds a 1-warp kernel that fits in cache │
  └───────────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘                                             
                  
  ---                                                                                                                                                                           
  Summary: The Fundamental Tradeoff

  Hand-written custom ops:
    + Algorithmic optimizations (FlashAttention, online softmax)                                                                                                                
    + In-place semantics (less HBM)                                                                                                                                             
    + Domain-specific tuning for target shapes                                                                                                                                  
    + Cross-layer fusion (allreduce+norm)                                                                                                                                       
    - Must be written manually for each op                                                                                                                                      
    - Fixed to the shapes/patterns author anticipated                                                                                                                           
                                                                                                                                                                                
  Inductor-generated Triton:                                                                                                                                                    
    + Automatically fuses PyTorch op sequences                                                                                                                                  
    + Autotuning searches kernel configs                                                                                                                                        
    + Works for any new op without manual work
    - Cannot change algorithms (only fuses existing ones)                                                                                                                       
    - Cannot write in-place (autograd safety)                                                                                                                                   
    - Search space may miss optimal configs                                                                                                                                     
    - Very slow to compile (max-autotune = benchmark every config)                                                                                                              
                                                                                                                                                                                
  This is exactly why SGLang's design is selective: use Inductor only for ops where it can win (RMSNorm, SiLU×Mul, RoPE at small bs), and keep custom kernels for ops where     
  algorithm matters (attention, FusedMoE at bs>1). The CustomOp.enter_torch_compile() switch is the mechanism that enforces this selection at capture time.  
